{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503172"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1941"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1941"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.5,0.16,0.24,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1941"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45072"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of intermittent headaches and episodes of extreme anxiety associated with palpitations and sweating. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks four glasses of wine on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 176/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her thyroid examination is normal. Abdominal examination reveals no striae, central adiposity, or renal bruits. Her BMI is 24 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Thyroid function tests, full blood count and basic metabolic panel are all within normal ranges.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum parathyroid hormone","24-hour urinary fractionated metanephrine","24-hour urinary free cortisol","24-hour urinary catecholamine metabolites","Aldosterone:Renin ratio"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of phaeochromocytoma: paroxysmal episodes of headache, anxiety, palpitations and sweating, along with hypertension in a young person. These catecholamine-secreting tumours typically arise from the adrenal medulla and require careful investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary fractionated metanephrine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial test, with 98% sensitivity and specificity for phaeochromocytoma. This test measures unconjugated noradrenaline (norepinephrine), adrenaline (epinephrine), and dopamine collected via an indwelling catheter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary catecholamine metabolites\u003C/strong\u003E (homovanillic acid and vanillylmandelic acid) can be used but are less sensitive and specific. While these metabolites are elevated in phaeochromocytoma, they may also be raised in other neuroendocrine tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum parathyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if hyperparathyroidism was suspected as a cause of secondary hypertension. However, patients with hyperparathyroidism typically present with other manifestations before developing symptomatic hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose Cushing\u0027s syndrome. While this can cause secondary hypertension, the absence of cushingoid features (such as central adiposity and striae) makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAldosterone:Renin ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is used to investigate primary hyperaldosteronism (Conn\u0027s syndrome), which typically presents with hypokalaemia and refractory hypertension. This patient\u0027s normal basic metabolic panel makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming elevated metanephrines, imaging studies would be required to localise the tumour. Treatment is surgical removal after appropriate alpha-blockade.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intermittent headaches, palpitations, and hypertension in a young patient should raise suspicion for phaeochromocytoma","24-hour urinary fractionated metanephrines is the most sensitive and specific initial test for diagnosing phaeochromocytoma","Secondary causes of hypertension should always be considered in young patients"],"references":["Neumann HPH, Young WF, Eng C. Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglionoma. N Engl J Med. 2019; 381:552-65. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1806651","Young WF. Clinical presentation and diagnosis of pheochromocytoma. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024; Accessed on January 31, 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-presentation-and-diagnosis-of-pheochromocytoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1941"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T14:02:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T14:04:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1941"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60254"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/